1
00:03:49,612 --> 00:03:52,080
It is better to settle
these matters in the courts...

2
00:03:52,282 --> 00:03:53,715
... than on the streets.

3
00:03:53,917 --> 00:03:56,852
And new laws are needed
at every level.

4
00:03:57,053 --> 00:04:00,420
But law alone cannot make
men see right.

5
00:04:00,990 --> 00:04:04,118
We are confronted primarily
with a moral issue.

6
00:04:04,327 --> 00:04:06,318
The heart of the question is...

7
00:04:06,529 --> 00:04:09,896
... whether all Americans are
to be afforded equal rights...

8
00:04:10,099 --> 00:04:11,862
...and equal opportunities...

9
00:04:12,702 --> 00:04:15,102
... whether we treat
our fellow Americans...

10
00:04:15,305 --> 00:04:16,636
...as we want to be treated.

11
00:04:16,839 --> 00:04:19,831
If an American,
because his skin is dark...

12
00:04:20,310 --> 00:04:23,837
...cannot eat lunch
in a restaurant open to the public...

13
00:04:24,047 --> 00:04:26,015
...if he cannot send his children...

14
00:04:26,215 --> 00:04:28,410
... to the best public school
available...

15
00:04:28,751 --> 00:04:32,482
...if he cannot vote
for the officials who represent him...

16
00:04:33,089 --> 00:04:36,058
...if, in short, he cannot enjoy
the full and free life...

17
00:04:36,259 --> 00:04:38,193
... which all of us want...

18
00:04:39,128 --> 00:04:41,460
... then who among us
would be content...

19
00:04:41,731 --> 00:04:43,892
... to have the color
of his skin changed?

20
00:04:44,734 --> 00:04:46,895
Who among us would then be content...

21
00:04:47,103 --> 00:04:50,300
... with the counsels
of patience and delay?

22
00:04:50,907 --> 00:04:53,432
One hundred years
of delay have passed...

23
00:04:53,643 --> 00:04:56,237
...since President Lincoln
freed the slaves...

24
00:04:56,713 --> 00:05:01,116
... yet their heirs, their grandsons
are not fully free.

25
00:05:01,484 --> 00:05:04,317
They are not yet freed
from the bonds of injustice.

26
00:05:04,654 --> 00:05:07,987
They are not yet freed
from social and economic oppression.

27
00:05:08,191 --> 00:05:10,091
That looks like a police car.

28
00:05:10,526 --> 00:05:14,326
And this nation, for all
its hopes and all its boasts...

29
00:05:14,530 --> 00:05:18,193
... will not be fully free
until all its citizens are free.

30
00:05:19,369 --> 00:05:22,463
We preach freedom
around the world and we mean it.

31
00:05:22,672 --> 00:05:25,004
And we cherish our freedom
here at home.

32
00:05:25,208 --> 00:05:26,800
Are we to say to the world...

33
00:05:27,010 --> 00:05:29,535
...and much more importantly,
to each other...

34
00:05:29,746 --> 00:05:33,182
... that this is a land of the free,
except for the Negroes?

35
00:05:33,583 --> 00:05:36,984
That we have no second-class citizens,
except Negroes?

36
00:05:37,286 --> 00:05:39,754
That we have no class
or caste system...

37
00:05:39,956 --> 00:05:44,222
...no ghettos, no master race,
except with respect to Negroes?

38
00:05:44,861 --> 00:05:48,888
Now the time has come for
this nation to fulfill its promise.

39
00:05:49,332 --> 00:05:51,300
The events in Birmingham
and elsewhere...

40
00:05:51,868 --> 00:05:55,702
...have so increased the cries
for equality that no city...

41
00:05:56,072 --> 00:05:59,803
...or state or legislative body
can prudently choose...

42
00:06:00,009 --> 00:06:01,271
... to ignore them.

43
00:06:01,477 --> 00:06:03,411
The fires of frustration
and discord...

44
00:06:03,613 --> 00:06:07,071
...are burning in every city,
North and South...

45
00:06:07,383 --> 00:06:09,874
... where legal remedies
are not at hand.

46
00:06:10,086 --> 00:06:12,418
Redress is sought in the streets.

47
00:06:13,089 --> 00:06:15,922
We face a moral crisis
as a country and a people.

48
00:06:16,826 --> 00:06:19,886
It cannot be met
by repressive police action.

49
00:06:20,229 --> 00:06:23,255
It is a time to act
in the Congress...

50
00:06:23,499 --> 00:06:26,559
...in your state
and local legislative body...

51
00:06:26,769 --> 00:06:30,261
...and above all,
in all of our daily lives.

52
00:06:30,473 --> 00:06:32,634
A great change is at hand...

53
00:06:32,875 --> 00:06:34,206
...and our task...

54
00:06:34,410 --> 00:06:37,675
...our obligation is to make
that revolution, that change...

55
00:06:38,247 --> 00:06:40,545
...peaceful and constructive for all.

56
00:06:40,750 --> 00:06:42,149
Those who do nothing...

57
00:06:42,485 --> 00:06:45,454
...are inviting shame
as well as violence.

58
00:06:46,055 --> 00:06:48,649
Those who act boldly
are recognizing right...

59
00:06:49,926 --> 00:06:51,393
...as well as reality.

60
00:06:52,728 --> 00:06:53,558
Medgar!

61
00:06:53,763 --> 00:06:55,492
-Get down!
-Get the baby!

62
00:06:59,836 --> 00:07:01,064
Medgar!

63
00:07:10,613 --> 00:07:12,308
Oh, my God!

64
00:07:15,651 --> 00:07:17,983
Daddy! Daddy!

65
00:07:18,187 --> 00:07:19,711
Daddy, I love you!

66
00:07:22,925 --> 00:07:24,688
Daddy, don't die!

67
00:07:25,995 --> 00:07:27,826
I want my daddy!

68
00:07:32,869 --> 00:07:34,564
Turn me loose.

69
00:07:35,304 --> 00:07:36,896
Turn me loose.

70
00:07:43,946 --> 00:07:47,973
Medgar Evers believed in this country.

71
00:07:48,784 --> 00:07:52,811
It now remains to be seen
whether his country believed in him.

72
00:08:10,373 --> 00:08:13,103
The Citizens Council's raised
thousands for your defense.

73
00:08:13,309 --> 00:08:15,436
Money's pouring in
from all over the South.

74
00:08:15,645 --> 00:08:18,113
Nice likeness.
What do you think, boys?

75
00:08:18,314 --> 00:08:20,077
Mr. Beckwith, glad to see you.

76
00:08:20,283 --> 00:08:22,274
Mighty glad to be here.

77
00:08:22,952 --> 00:08:25,420
And isn't it true
your husband was the first...

78
00:08:25,621 --> 00:08:28,522
...to attempt to integrate
the University of Mississippi?

79
00:08:30,159 --> 00:08:32,787
At the time of his death,
he was involved in a lawsuit...

80
00:08:32,995 --> 00:08:35,862
...to integrate the public
school system, wasn't he?

81
00:08:37,500 --> 00:08:40,765
Your husband must've had quite
a few enemies, would you agree?

82
00:08:40,970 --> 00:08:42,267
Yes, he did.

83
00:08:42,471 --> 00:08:45,702
Your eldest boy,
his name is Kenyatta, isn't it?

84
00:08:45,975 --> 00:08:48,239
Darrell Kenyatta Evers.

85
00:08:48,611 --> 00:08:50,579
Kenyatta's a Mau Mau name, isn't it?

86
00:08:50,780 --> 00:08:51,769
Objection.

87
00:08:51,981 --> 00:08:53,175
Sustained.

88
00:08:53,382 --> 00:08:57,546
Isn't it true that over 100 people
were arrested during a demonstration...

89
00:08:57,753 --> 00:08:59,948
...that your husband
organized boycotting...

90
00:09:00,456 --> 00:09:04,051
...a department store in downtown
Jackson known as Kennington's?

91
00:09:04,327 --> 00:09:05,658
Who's that?

92
00:09:06,329 --> 00:09:07,557
Ross Barnett.

93
00:09:07,763 --> 00:09:09,230
You're kidding.

94
00:09:09,832 --> 00:09:12,858
Nope. You don't see that
every day of the week.

95
00:09:13,069 --> 00:09:17,005
A former governor shaking hands
with an assassin in front of the jury.

96
00:09:17,206 --> 00:09:20,369
There's not a court in America
that would stand for that.

97
00:09:20,576 --> 00:09:22,703
What's America got to do
with anything?

98
00:09:22,912 --> 00:09:24,573
This is Mississippi.

99
00:09:25,047 --> 00:09:27,015
Byron De La Beckwith.

100
00:09:27,416 --> 00:09:30,078
-You live in Greenwood, Mississippi?
-Y es, sir.

101
00:09:30,286 --> 00:09:32,220
My mother was a Yerger.

102
00:09:32,421 --> 00:09:34,286
Her mother was Susan Yerger...

103
00:09:34,490 --> 00:09:37,482
...a close personal friend
of Mrs. Jefferson Davis.

104
00:09:37,693 --> 00:09:39,388
You shoot Medgar Evers?

105
00:09:39,595 --> 00:09:40,755
No, sir!

106
00:09:41,797 --> 00:09:43,697
Your Honor, may l?

107
00:09:44,500 --> 00:09:46,866
Mr. Beckwith, is this your rifle?

108
00:09:47,637 --> 00:09:48,535
Let's see.

109
00:09:51,040 --> 00:09:54,271
Well, it bears a similarity...

110
00:09:54,477 --> 00:09:56,570
...but I couldn't say for certain.

111
00:09:56,812 --> 00:09:59,542
I don't record the
serial numbers of my weapons...

112
00:09:59,749 --> 00:10:04,379
...and my gun was stolen
from my home several days before...

113
00:10:04,654 --> 00:10:06,178
...this whole business.

114
00:10:36,819 --> 00:10:38,514
How do you feel, Delay?

115
00:10:38,754 --> 00:10:41,245
I got tears in my eyes.

116
00:10:41,490 --> 00:10:42,787
For Dixie, huh?

117
00:11:03,312 --> 00:11:04,438
In summation...

118
00:11:04,647 --> 00:11:08,014
...not only did surveillance cameras
provide us with a visual record...

119
00:11:08,351 --> 00:11:10,080
...of the crime being committed...

120
00:11:10,286 --> 00:11:14,689
...but four eyewitnesses observed
the defendant removing his mask...

121
00:11:14,890 --> 00:11:17,381
...upon exiting the convenience store.

122
00:11:17,860 --> 00:11:21,489
Short of you ladies and gentlemen
attending the actual event...

123
00:11:21,697 --> 00:11:24,962
...we don't feel the state
could have a stronger case.

124
00:11:25,201 --> 00:11:26,031
Thank you.

125
00:11:27,069 --> 00:11:28,195
Counsel?

126
00:11:29,939 --> 00:11:31,873
Hey, Bobby. How'd it go?

127
00:11:32,174 --> 00:11:34,836
Through a combination
of superior lawyering...

128
00:11:35,044 --> 00:11:39,208
...and a less than stellar performance
by our criminal, I got a conviction.

129
00:11:39,415 --> 00:11:40,507
Congratulations.

130
00:11:40,750 --> 00:11:44,982
My rape victim's reluctant to testify.
Can you handle the Harrison motion?

131
00:11:45,187 --> 00:11:46,779
-You bet.
-You're a lifesaver.

132
00:11:46,989 --> 00:11:49,958
-DeLaughter, your wife just called.
-What'd she want?

133
00:11:50,159 --> 00:11:54,493
To remind you you're having lunch with
her mother and your parents at 1:00.

134
00:11:54,697 --> 00:11:56,494
How could I forget?

135
00:11:56,732 --> 00:11:57,824
Bobby.

136
00:12:00,202 --> 00:12:02,636
-You seen this?
-Yes, I have.

137
00:12:02,838 --> 00:12:06,296
Evers' widow is calling for
the re-prosecution of De La Beckwith.

138
00:12:06,509 --> 00:12:08,943
Ed, this guy was killed
over 25 years ago.

139
00:12:09,445 --> 00:12:13,176
Dig up whatever you can on Medgar Evers
and be in my office at 3:00.

140
00:12:13,382 --> 00:12:14,872
Ed, this is ridiculous.

141
00:12:15,084 --> 00:12:16,142
Well, sure it is.

142
00:12:16,352 --> 00:12:17,649
But if we try to bury this...

143
00:12:17,853 --> 00:12:20,947
...she'll have every black politician
climbing all over me.

144
00:12:21,824 --> 00:12:23,951
My office, 3:00.

145
00:12:33,969 --> 00:12:36,403
Do we have any files here
on Medgar Evers?

146
00:12:36,605 --> 00:12:37,435
Who?

147
00:12:37,640 --> 00:12:41,371
The civil rights leader
that got himself shot in the 1960s?

148
00:12:41,577 --> 00:12:45,843
I just saw that file. It was next
to the one on the Lindbergh baby.

149
00:12:46,215 --> 00:12:48,649
Clara, just bring me what we have.

150
00:12:59,295 --> 00:13:00,626
Good afternoon, sir.

151
00:13:11,640 --> 00:13:13,904
Did you make Hinds County safer today?

152
00:13:14,109 --> 00:13:18,239
You know how it is with criminals.
It's like finding a gray hair.

153
00:13:18,481 --> 00:13:21,143
You pull one and two more pop up
to take its place.

154
00:13:21,917 --> 00:13:24,613
I love those earrings.
Have you worn them before?

155
00:13:24,820 --> 00:13:28,950
I've had them for quite some time.
I just never wear them during the day.

156
00:13:29,158 --> 00:13:32,355
You see that nonsense
about the Sovereignty Commission?

157
00:13:32,561 --> 00:13:34,256
Yeah, isn't that awful?

158
00:13:34,730 --> 00:13:38,029
That fool, Rea Hederman.
Since he took over that paper...

159
00:13:38,234 --> 00:13:41,601
...Iiberals like Jerry Mitchell
been trying to rewrite history.

160
00:13:42,037 --> 00:13:46,497
The Sovereignty Commission was a fine
organization that did a lot of good.

161
00:13:46,775 --> 00:13:49,005
Dixie, would you pass me the butter?

162
00:13:49,278 --> 00:13:52,679
Why do they dig up things
that happened 25 years ago anyway?

163
00:13:52,882 --> 00:13:55,680
Medgar Evers' widow
wants to reopen the case.

164
00:13:56,185 --> 00:13:58,016
You can't be serious.

165
00:13:58,354 --> 00:14:00,288
Ed asked me to look into it.

166
00:14:03,959 --> 00:14:06,086
You just tell him, "No, thank you."

167
00:14:06,295 --> 00:14:10,664
When will these people get it through
their heads that the '60s are over?

168
00:14:10,866 --> 00:14:14,302
The 1860s and the 1960s.

169
00:14:14,537 --> 00:14:17,529
I thought they found
that Beckwith fella not guilty.

170
00:14:17,740 --> 00:14:20,573
Actually, there were two hung juries.

171
00:14:21,810 --> 00:14:25,211
The reason I know is because
my late husband, Judge Moore...

172
00:14:25,414 --> 00:14:27,746
...was a spectator
at both those trials.

173
00:14:28,083 --> 00:14:30,449
He'd never miss a day.
And he told me...

174
00:14:30,719 --> 00:14:35,315
...that they'd never convict Beckwith,
no matter how many trials they had.

175
00:14:35,658 --> 00:14:39,025
It's just political. I don't
think anything will come of it.

176
00:14:39,228 --> 00:14:41,628
Son, for your sake,
it had better not.

177
00:14:41,830 --> 00:14:43,695
You want to be a judge someday.

178
00:14:43,899 --> 00:14:47,767
You persecute a 70-year-old man,
guilty or not, over some nigger...

179
00:14:47,970 --> 00:14:51,428
...you'll have everybody in Mississippi
lined up against you.

180
00:14:51,640 --> 00:14:53,232
-Hey, Howard.
-How you doing?

181
00:14:53,442 --> 00:14:56,070
Y'all got any
of that crawdad chowder today?

182
00:14:56,278 --> 00:14:57,472
Yes, sir.

183
00:14:57,680 --> 00:15:00,513
-How many for crawdad chowder?
-Oh, come on!

184
00:15:02,251 --> 00:15:05,948
Mrs. Evers, Mr. Dees, I'm Jerry Mitchell
from The Clarion-Ledger.

185
00:15:06,155 --> 00:15:09,147
I broke the story on the jury
tampering in your husband's case.

186
00:15:10,492 --> 00:15:11,891
-I talked to you on the phone.
-That's right.

187
00:15:12,094 --> 00:15:16,292
Thank you for your good work. I can't
tell you how much it's appreciated.

188
00:15:16,498 --> 00:15:18,261
I'm just doing my job, ma'am.

189
00:15:18,467 --> 00:15:22,460
What do you think your chances are
of getting the D.A. to reopen the case?

190
00:15:22,671 --> 00:15:24,662
I've passed this way before.

191
00:15:24,873 --> 00:15:28,866
Let's just say I've adopted
an attitude of tempered optimism.

192
00:15:32,348 --> 00:15:33,975
DeLaughter, hear the news?

193
00:15:34,183 --> 00:15:36,344
President Lincoln just got shot.

194
00:15:36,552 --> 00:15:38,816
Some guy named Booth did it.

195
00:15:40,322 --> 00:15:44,281
The Sovereignty Commission, a state
agency, worked against the D.A...

196
00:15:44,493 --> 00:15:48,486
...to ensure the jury had Beckwith
sympathizers to keep him out of jail.

197
00:15:48,697 --> 00:15:50,858
That's grounds for a new trial.

198
00:15:51,066 --> 00:15:52,158
With all due respect...

199
00:15:52,368 --> 00:15:55,701
...those old files have been
leaking out for years.

200
00:15:55,904 --> 00:16:00,136
They only ran background checks which,
while unethical, was not illegal.

201
00:16:00,342 --> 00:16:04,574
We can't prove jury tampering.
I'd like you to meet Bob DeLaughter.

202
00:16:05,047 --> 00:16:05,877
How do you do?

203
00:16:06,248 --> 00:16:08,148
-Pleasure.
-Mr. Morris Dees...

204
00:16:08,350 --> 00:16:09,874
...the Southern Poverty Law Center.

205
00:16:10,119 --> 00:16:11,814
-How you doing?
-I was explaining...

206
00:16:12,021 --> 00:16:13,818
...that in order for us
to pursue this...

207
00:16:14,023 --> 00:16:16,491
...we'll need more
than an article in a newspaper.

208
00:16:16,692 --> 00:16:18,057
We'll need new evidence.

209
00:16:18,260 --> 00:16:20,160
In 1964, you had
a mountain of evidence.

210
00:16:20,362 --> 00:16:22,159
All you gotta do is retry Beckwith.

211
00:16:22,364 --> 00:16:24,889
On the basis of that alone,
you'll get a conviction.

212
00:16:26,168 --> 00:16:29,399
As you can see, the mountain
has crumbled a bit.

213
00:16:30,539 --> 00:16:31,528
What's this?

214
00:16:31,740 --> 00:16:35,437
That's all that's left of the
state's case against De La Beckwith.

215
00:16:35,644 --> 00:16:38,579
Just a few pages
of the old police report.

216
00:16:38,781 --> 00:16:41,579
-Where's the gun? Where--
-Where's the bullet?

217
00:16:41,850 --> 00:16:45,684
Where's the original trial transcript?
Where are the files? Beats me.

218
00:16:47,322 --> 00:16:49,119
Are you telling us it is lost?

219
00:16:49,324 --> 00:16:51,189
I'm telling you, we don't have it.

220
00:16:51,493 --> 00:16:52,721
Well, that's outrageous.

221
00:16:53,562 --> 00:16:56,463
Even if we had the evidence,
we'd never get around...

222
00:16:56,665 --> 00:16:59,862
...to the Sixth Amendment right
to a speedy trial.

223
00:17:00,069 --> 00:17:04,062
Mr. Dees would agree that 25 years
isn't exactly what you'd call speedy.

224
00:17:05,140 --> 00:17:06,767
May I see that?

225
00:17:06,975 --> 00:17:09,068
Mrs. Evers, this is
pretty strong stuff.

226
00:17:09,912 --> 00:17:11,140
I'd like to see it.

227
00:17:21,090 --> 00:17:23,581
"June 13, 1963.

228
00:17:23,892 --> 00:17:26,224
To the Jackson Police Department:

229
00:17:26,562 --> 00:17:30,430
When you catch whoever killed
the nigger, pin a medal on him...

230
00:17:30,833 --> 00:17:34,667
...because he just did Mississippi
one hell of a favor.

231
00:17:35,771 --> 00:17:38,433
June 14, 1963.

232
00:17:38,640 --> 00:17:41,473
A female who refused
to identify herself stated...

233
00:17:41,677 --> 00:17:44,908
...that she'd heard a rumor
that Medgar Evers' wife...

234
00:17:45,147 --> 00:17:49,083
...had gotten jealous of Lena Horne,
who appeared with Evers at a rally...

235
00:17:49,284 --> 00:17:52,845
...and might have gotten
her brother-in-law to kill Evers."

236
00:17:55,524 --> 00:17:59,255
Who wouldn't be jealous of Lena Horne?
What a beautiful woman.

237
00:18:00,295 --> 00:18:01,523
Y es, ma'am.

238
00:18:01,730 --> 00:18:06,326
The cops wrote that garbage down
because they actually took it seriously.

239
00:18:06,535 --> 00:18:07,467
Mr. Dees.

240
00:18:08,036 --> 00:18:12,200
Do you think the police in Washington,
D.C. would have written it up...

241
00:18:12,407 --> 00:18:16,138
...if some nitwit said Jackie Kennedy
had a hand in J.F.K.'s death...

242
00:18:16,345 --> 00:18:19,143
...because her husband ran around
with Marilyn Monroe?

243
00:18:19,381 --> 00:18:20,507
What's your point?

244
00:18:20,716 --> 00:18:23,776
The murder of Medgar Evers
was a race crime...

245
00:18:23,986 --> 00:18:26,011
...a political crime.
An assassination.

246
00:18:26,388 --> 00:18:28,356
Beckwith is free today...

247
00:18:28,557 --> 00:18:31,082
...thanks to a racist jury,
a racist police department...

248
00:18:31,293 --> 00:18:33,454
...and a racist D.A.'s office.

249
00:18:33,662 --> 00:18:36,130
Twenty-five years ago,
Waller and this office...

250
00:18:36,331 --> 00:18:38,458
...went after Beckwith
not once but twice.

251
00:18:38,667 --> 00:18:40,726
I don't need to sit here and listen--

252
00:18:41,436 --> 00:18:44,701
Twenty-five years ago,
I sat on the witness stand...

253
00:18:44,907 --> 00:18:48,138
...and I watched as the former
governor of this state...

254
00:18:48,343 --> 00:18:51,506
...shook hands with the man
who murdered my husband...

255
00:18:52,314 --> 00:18:54,009
...while I was on the stand.

256
00:18:57,085 --> 00:18:58,985
I don't expect you to understand...

257
00:18:59,188 --> 00:19:01,622
...the pain and suffering
my family went through...

258
00:19:01,824 --> 00:19:03,485
...but I did come here thinking...

259
00:19:03,692 --> 00:19:07,389
...that this office might want
to see justice finally served.

260
00:19:10,499 --> 00:19:13,935
You've given me all the reasons
why you can't pursue this.

261
00:19:14,136 --> 00:19:17,264
Perhaps you can find
one reason why you can.

262
00:19:17,906 --> 00:19:19,703
Good afternoon, gentlemen.

263
00:19:39,628 --> 00:19:41,118
Ed Peters is a good man...

264
00:19:41,330 --> 00:19:43,924
...but as you can see,
we simply don't have a case.

265
00:19:44,132 --> 00:19:47,966
I know you've been living
with this thing for a long while...

266
00:19:48,971 --> 00:19:51,132
...but maybe it's just time you....

267
00:19:52,207 --> 00:19:53,469
Let it go?

268
00:19:54,042 --> 00:19:56,909
I can understand why you'd
think that, Mr. DeLaughter.

269
00:19:57,112 --> 00:19:59,478
For years, I said
the same thing to Medgar.

270
00:19:59,681 --> 00:20:02,411
"Let it go.
Let's get out of Mississippi."

271
00:20:02,918 --> 00:20:04,715
Do you know what he said to me?

272
00:20:05,320 --> 00:20:07,811
" I don't know if I'm going
to heaven or to hell...

273
00:20:08,023 --> 00:20:10,150
...but I'm going from Jackson."

274
00:20:10,759 --> 00:20:12,556
Good afternoon, Mr. DeLaughter.

275
00:20:45,327 --> 00:20:47,192
Hey, everybody, I'm home.

276
00:20:55,604 --> 00:20:56,798
Hey, tiger.

277
00:20:57,472 --> 00:20:58,700
Hi, Dad.

278
00:20:59,641 --> 00:21:03,543
You sure you got enough distractions?
I can go get your Game Boy.

279
00:21:04,146 --> 00:21:05,272
Dad.

280
00:21:05,480 --> 00:21:06,708
Hi, Daddy.

281
00:21:07,149 --> 00:21:08,081
Hi, Dad.

282
00:21:08,283 --> 00:21:12,344
-Did you bring me a lollipop?
-I did. I got one for Claire too.

283
00:21:12,554 --> 00:21:15,523
-Thanks, Daddy.
-How was school today, sweetie?

284
00:21:15,724 --> 00:21:18,022
Did Miss Collins like
the bracelet you made?

285
00:21:18,327 --> 00:21:20,056
Daddy, tell us a story.

286
00:21:20,762 --> 00:21:23,629
-A real scary one.
-Claire, you want to hear a story?

287
00:21:23,832 --> 00:21:25,800
Okay, but not too scary.

288
00:21:26,001 --> 00:21:29,698
Let's go to Mommy and Daddy's room,
because we don't wanna disturb Burt.

289
00:21:33,075 --> 00:21:36,602
-You want something to eat?
-No, I got something at the office.

290
00:21:38,447 --> 00:21:40,176
Thanks for letting me know.

291
00:22:22,958 --> 00:22:24,516
Honey, what are you doing up?

292
00:22:24,726 --> 00:22:26,193
I can't sleep.

293
00:22:26,395 --> 00:22:28,056
The ghost is back.

294
00:22:28,463 --> 00:22:30,556
I'll go. I'll go.

295
00:22:31,700 --> 00:22:34,601
The ghost is back?
Where is he this time?

296
00:22:34,803 --> 00:22:35,770
In my bed.

297
00:22:35,971 --> 00:22:39,065
Really? We'll just have
to see about that.

298
00:22:42,477 --> 00:22:45,310
You were right.
He's right there on the bed.

299
00:22:46,014 --> 00:22:47,106
No, Daddy.

300
00:22:47,315 --> 00:22:49,476
Now he's over by the window.

301
00:22:51,887 --> 00:22:53,149
I see.

302
00:22:54,790 --> 00:22:57,088
Your bottle tree was
supposed to keep him away.

303
00:22:57,426 --> 00:23:00,088
Maybe I don't have
the right kind of bottles.

304
00:23:00,429 --> 00:23:01,828
You know, baby...

305
00:23:02,898 --> 00:23:05,332
...when we lived in Natchez,
there was a ghost...

306
00:23:05,534 --> 00:23:07,126
...that lived right next door...

307
00:23:07,335 --> 00:23:10,463
...in the remains of this house
that got burned during the war.

308
00:23:10,939 --> 00:23:14,807
And sometimes he'd come over
and get right in my closet.

309
00:23:15,110 --> 00:23:16,304
How'd you make him go away?

310
00:23:16,678 --> 00:23:19,078
Granny would come in
and sing a song...

311
00:23:19,281 --> 00:23:21,306
...and before you knew it,
he was gone.

312
00:23:22,050 --> 00:23:23,608
What'd she sing?

313
00:23:24,052 --> 00:23:26,919
She sang the song every ghost
from Mississippi loves.

314
00:23:27,422 --> 00:23:28,514
Sing it, Daddy.

315
00:23:29,024 --> 00:23:30,184
All right.

316
00:23:31,560 --> 00:23:34,688
I wish I was in the land of cotton

317
00:23:34,896 --> 00:23:37,126
Old times there are not forgotten

318
00:23:37,332 --> 00:23:38,629
Look away

319
00:23:38,934 --> 00:23:40,265
Look away

320
00:23:40,535 --> 00:23:43,834
Look away, Dixieland

321
00:23:44,039 --> 00:23:46,371
In Dixieland where I was born

322
00:23:46,708 --> 00:23:49,336
Early on one frosty morn'

323
00:23:49,678 --> 00:23:52,306
Look away, look away

324
00:23:52,514 --> 00:23:55,642
Look away, Dixieland

325
00:23:56,218 --> 00:23:58,448
Oh, I wish I was in Dixie

326
00:23:58,653 --> 00:24:01,417
Hooray, hooray

327
00:24:01,623 --> 00:24:04,319
In Dixieland I'll take my stand

328
00:24:04,526 --> 00:24:07,495
To live and die in Dixie

329
00:24:07,696 --> 00:24:09,789
Away, away

330
00:24:10,065 --> 00:24:12,659
Away down South

331
00:24:13,101 --> 00:24:14,932
In Dixie

332
00:24:18,940 --> 00:24:21,272
I'd ask what's new,
but I'm afraid you'd tell me.

333
00:24:21,476 --> 00:24:24,036
My readers are on the edge
of their collective seat.

334
00:24:25,413 --> 00:24:26,880
Will Mr. DeLaughter go after
Byron De La Beckwith?

335
00:24:27,082 --> 00:24:31,485
The D.A.'s office will investigate
the possibility of reopening the case.

336
00:24:31,686 --> 00:24:35,053
I didn't go to law school,
but that sounds like bullshit.

337
00:24:35,257 --> 00:24:36,315
Nice talking to you.

338
00:24:36,525 --> 00:24:38,015
Have a nice day.

339
00:24:59,581 --> 00:25:03,017
Can you tell me how I can get
ahold of Lewis Skinner...

340
00:25:03,218 --> 00:25:04,310
...or Fred Sanders?

341
00:25:04,519 --> 00:25:08,751
If you want Lewis Skinner, you'll need
a shovel and six hours of digging time.

342
00:25:09,157 --> 00:25:10,283
What's Fred's status?

343
00:25:10,492 --> 00:25:13,222
As far as I know,
he's still aboveground.

344
00:25:14,863 --> 00:25:17,388
Back in '63,
none of those houses were there.

345
00:25:17,599 --> 00:25:19,590
That was all vacant lot.

346
00:25:19,801 --> 00:25:22,736
And this here was
all covered over with brush.

347
00:25:22,971 --> 00:25:26,031
I got out here eight minutes
after the call came in.

348
00:25:26,241 --> 00:25:30,473
The way Mrs. Evers yelled at me,
you'd think I was the one who done it.

349
00:25:31,680 --> 00:25:35,912
This is where they found the gun,
hidden in some honeysuckle vines.

350
00:25:36,384 --> 00:25:38,443
Any idea where
that gun might be today?

351
00:25:38,653 --> 00:25:39,711
Hell, no.

352
00:25:39,921 --> 00:25:41,013
Back in those days...

353
00:25:41,223 --> 00:25:44,818
...evidence had a habit
of disappearing after the trials.

354
00:25:45,293 --> 00:25:46,419
Look at that.

355
00:25:46,628 --> 00:25:49,756
My grandmother could have
picked Evers off from over here.

356
00:25:49,965 --> 00:25:51,865
That's where he was shot.

357
00:25:52,067 --> 00:25:54,592
That big tree wasn't there
at the time.

358
00:25:54,936 --> 00:25:56,460
There was blood everywhere.

359
00:25:56,671 --> 00:25:59,572
All over the driveway,
all over the car.

360
00:25:59,774 --> 00:26:02,140
It was as if somebody
had butchered a hog.

361
00:26:02,377 --> 00:26:07,110
But Evers must've been one hell of a
strong man because somehow he managed...

362
00:26:07,315 --> 00:26:09,647
...to drag himself
all the way up to his door.

363
00:26:09,985 --> 00:26:13,978
After that bullet tore through his back,
it slammed through that window...

364
00:26:14,189 --> 00:26:15,656
...crashed through a wall...

365
00:26:15,857 --> 00:26:19,725
...ricocheted off the refrigerator
and busted the coffeepot.

366
00:26:19,928 --> 00:26:24,024
We found it on the kitchen counter
next to a watermelon.

367
00:26:25,367 --> 00:26:26,459
You're kidding me.

368
00:26:26,868 --> 00:26:28,096
No, sir.

369
00:26:33,074 --> 00:26:34,439
Did he have any kids?

370
00:26:34,643 --> 00:26:38,977
If my memory serves, I believe there
were three little ones there that night.

371
00:26:43,385 --> 00:26:47,947
What kind of man shoots another man
in the back in front of his family?

372
00:26:49,124 --> 00:26:51,649
I love the land of my birth.

373
00:26:52,427 --> 00:26:55,021
I do not mean
just America as a country...

374
00:26:55,263 --> 00:26:56,787
...but Mississippi...

375
00:26:56,998 --> 00:26:58,659
... the state in which I was born.

376
00:26:59,768 --> 00:27:02,794
So the deplorable things
I speak of here today...

377
00:27:03,038 --> 00:27:05,336
... will be said to you
in hopes of a future...

378
00:27:06,107 --> 00:27:09,338
... where such will not
be the case in Mississippi.

379
00:27:09,544 --> 00:27:11,307
In the horrific deaths...

380
00:27:11,513 --> 00:27:13,003
...of Emmett Till...

381
00:27:13,381 --> 00:27:15,576
...Reverend G. W. Lee...

382
00:27:15,950 --> 00:27:18,680
...Lamar Smith and a variety
of other atrocities...

383
00:27:18,887 --> 00:27:21,321
...no one has been convicted.

384
00:27:21,923 --> 00:27:26,690
And we feel those guilty of having
committed these ungodly acts...

385
00:27:26,895 --> 00:27:30,456
...had the feeling of assurance
that nothing ever would be done.

386
00:27:30,765 --> 00:27:33,029
For you see, ladies and gentlemen...

387
00:27:33,668 --> 00:27:37,900
... white juries have yet to convict
a white man in Mississippi...

388
00:27:38,173 --> 00:27:40,698
...guilty of a crime against a Negro.

389
00:27:41,476 --> 00:27:46,072
The failure of the so-called decent
or moderate white person...

390
00:27:46,281 --> 00:27:49,717
... to take a positive
and uncompromising stand....

391
00:27:49,918 --> 00:27:51,180
Who's that?

392
00:27:52,754 --> 00:27:54,119
Medgar Evers.

393
00:27:57,225 --> 00:27:58,852
Why are you looking at it?

394
00:28:00,995 --> 00:28:04,453
I just wanted to get
an idea of who he was.

395
00:28:05,500 --> 00:28:07,866
I'd like to get
an idea of who you are.

396
00:28:08,503 --> 00:28:10,232
What's that supposed to mean?

397
00:28:10,972 --> 00:28:13,440
I was willing to go down
that road with you...

398
00:28:13,641 --> 00:28:16,701
...when you got out of law school
and did that pro bono work.

399
00:28:16,911 --> 00:28:20,438
And when you worked for
that Jew lawyer who ran you ragged.

400
00:28:20,915 --> 00:28:24,715
I minded a little when you turned down
that offer from Morse & Braggs...

401
00:28:24,919 --> 00:28:27,786
...so you could be assistant D.A.
at one-fourth the salary.

402
00:28:27,989 --> 00:28:31,356
But I'll be damned if I spent
10 years supporting your career...

403
00:28:31,559 --> 00:28:32,958
...just so you can humiliate me.

404
00:28:33,561 --> 00:28:35,825
You're gonna pursue this, aren't you?

405
00:28:36,831 --> 00:28:39,891
You're gonna humiliate me
in front of my friends...

406
00:28:40,101 --> 00:28:42,194
...my family and the entire state.

407
00:28:42,404 --> 00:28:44,429
I'm just looking
at a couple of tapes.

408
00:28:45,039 --> 00:28:47,564
Fine. Look at your tapes.

409
00:28:47,876 --> 00:28:49,605
That's all you'd better do.

410
00:28:55,216 --> 00:28:56,774
-Why not?
-Because you can't win.

411
00:28:56,985 --> 00:28:57,815
Who says?

412
00:28:58,086 --> 00:29:00,919
-The Sixth Amendment.
-Suppose I could get around it.

413
00:29:01,122 --> 00:29:04,387
It's one thing for
the grieving widow to carry on--

414
00:29:04,793 --> 00:29:08,695
Suppose an argument could be made
that the Sixth Amendment doesn't apply.

415
00:29:08,897 --> 00:29:10,421
You want to retry Beckwith?

416
00:29:10,665 --> 00:29:11,597
Fine.

417
00:29:11,866 --> 00:29:16,667
Dig up 26-year-old physical evidence
which probably no longer exists...

418
00:29:17,105 --> 00:29:21,235
...identify it, and then you'll have
to locate the key witnesses...

419
00:29:21,443 --> 00:29:24,207
...who, if you find them,
are probably dead or senile.

420
00:29:24,412 --> 00:29:26,880
Their testimony could be read
from the transcript.

421
00:29:27,081 --> 00:29:30,778
We haven't seen a certified
transcript in over 25 years.

422
00:29:30,985 --> 00:29:33,510
-What if I found one?
-Let's say, by some miracle...

423
00:29:33,721 --> 00:29:37,282
...you found one, got an indictment.
Then by some greater miracle...

424
00:29:37,492 --> 00:29:41,656
...the state Supreme Court and U.S.
Supreme Court didn't throw it out...

425
00:29:41,863 --> 00:29:44,525
...and you actually got to trial.
What if you lose?

426
00:29:44,732 --> 00:29:48,668
The whole state, which is supposed
to have changed so much...

427
00:29:48,870 --> 00:29:51,566
...will be facing the worst
public relations disaster...

428
00:29:51,773 --> 00:29:55,038
...since that black kid, Emmett Till,
bobbed up out of the river.

429
00:30:00,682 --> 00:30:02,912
Are you telling me
I can't go after this?

430
00:30:03,117 --> 00:30:05,347
I'm telling you
you're dealing with the past.

431
00:30:05,553 --> 00:30:07,987
Mississippi's not
a place you wanna be.

432
00:30:12,694 --> 00:30:15,822
Hopefully, Jerry Mitchell can
keep this thing alive for us.

433
00:30:16,064 --> 00:30:19,261
Jerry Mitchell's fine, but
what we need is national press.

434
00:30:19,467 --> 00:30:24,029
Darrell, CNN won't run a major story
about how the D.A. of Hinds County...

435
00:30:24,239 --> 00:30:27,208
...is refusing to re-prosecute a case...

436
00:30:27,408 --> 00:30:29,399
...that's a quarter of a century old.

437
00:30:29,611 --> 00:30:32,171
Stop annoying your grandmama.

438
00:30:32,380 --> 00:30:36,578
The greatest joy in your mother's life
is being annoyed by her grandchildren.

439
00:30:36,784 --> 00:30:39,218
Next to being annoyed by you, Walter.

440
00:30:39,954 --> 00:30:40,921
I'll get it.

441
00:30:41,122 --> 00:30:43,181
I'm not here no matter who it is.

442
00:30:49,464 --> 00:30:50,488
Who?

443
00:30:52,400 --> 00:30:54,163
Just a minute, please.

444
00:30:55,003 --> 00:30:56,698
I want you to eat those beans.

445
00:30:56,905 --> 00:30:58,600
It's long distance from Jackson.

446
00:30:58,840 --> 00:31:01,741
A man by the name of DeLaughter.
You want me to take it?

447
00:31:01,943 --> 00:31:03,808
No, I'll take it.

448
00:31:04,112 --> 00:31:05,773
Eat those beans.

449
00:31:06,548 --> 00:31:08,448
I don't eat beans.

450
00:31:13,721 --> 00:31:14,881
Hello, Mrs. Evers.

451
00:31:15,089 --> 00:31:18,320
I know you probably left here
feeling pretty discouraged...

452
00:31:18,526 --> 00:31:21,893
...but I hope you understand
Mr. Peters was just being realistic.

453
00:31:22,096 --> 00:31:23,757
I understand perfectly.

454
00:31:23,965 --> 00:31:25,330
I also wanted you to know...

455
00:31:25,533 --> 00:31:28,366
...that we are going to
be keeping this case open.

456
00:31:31,306 --> 00:31:32,432
Mrs. Evers?

457
00:31:32,640 --> 00:31:35,803
Did it suddenly occur to
Mr. Peters that he'd better...

458
00:31:36,010 --> 00:31:39,946
...start making nice with the
black community before November?

459
00:31:40,515 --> 00:31:42,676
-Mrs. Evers--
-He made it clear to me...

460
00:31:42,917 --> 00:31:46,114
...that in addition to having
no evidence and no witnesses...

461
00:31:46,321 --> 00:31:47,982
...he also had no interest.

462
00:31:48,222 --> 00:31:52,454
Looking into this wasn't so much
Mr. Peter's idea as it was mine.

463
00:31:52,660 --> 00:31:54,821
-Yours?
-Yes, ma'am.

464
00:31:57,398 --> 00:32:00,993
Judge Russel Moore was perhaps
the most racist judge...

465
00:32:01,202 --> 00:32:03,466
...in the history
of the state of Mississippi.

466
00:32:03,671 --> 00:32:06,606
Why would his son-in-law
be interested in this case?

467
00:32:06,874 --> 00:32:10,640
Mrs. Evers, I'm 37 years old,
just like Medgar was...

468
00:32:10,845 --> 00:32:13,177
...and I've got three kids,
like he did.

469
00:32:13,581 --> 00:32:16,175
I was 11 years old
when your husband was killed...

470
00:32:16,384 --> 00:32:18,511
...and I hardly remember him at all.

471
00:32:19,520 --> 00:32:23,684
But I went by your house the other day
and I could see him there...

472
00:32:24,525 --> 00:32:26,356
...watering his lawn...

473
00:32:26,928 --> 00:32:28,691
... working on his roof...

474
00:32:29,497 --> 00:32:31,431
...playing with his children.

475
00:32:32,100 --> 00:32:36,093
No man has the right to take
another man away from his children.

476
00:32:37,872 --> 00:32:40,534
I appreciate the call,
Mr. DeLaughter.

477
00:32:41,209 --> 00:32:43,109
I'll keep in touch, Mrs. Evers.

478
00:32:48,716 --> 00:32:50,411
Did you plan on telling me...

479
00:32:50,952 --> 00:32:53,614
...or was I just gonna read
about it in the papers?

480
00:32:55,723 --> 00:32:58,556
We should be at the
Walkers' house in 15 minutes.

481
00:33:00,061 --> 00:33:02,791
Well, I've got a lot
of work to do here.

482
00:33:06,901 --> 00:33:08,266
Suit yourself.

483
00:33:13,374 --> 00:33:16,275
Nobody gives a goddamn
what Byron De La Beckwith did...

484
00:33:16,477 --> 00:33:18,741
...to some Medgar Evers 26 years ago.

485
00:33:18,946 --> 00:33:22,814
Hell, Larry Smith got shot down
in his own driveway just last week.

486
00:33:23,117 --> 00:33:24,880
And it wasn't for no civil rights.

